                                This is the structural alteration to housing program administered by the VARO.  This field allows you to enter the veteran's use and eligibility for this grant.  


2041.7,14     VA VOCATIONAL REHABILITATION 0;15 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Enter eligibility for and use of VA Voc Rehab benefits. 
              DESCRIPTION:
                                This denotes if the veteran has participated in the VA vocational rehabilitation program.  


2041.7,15     VIST ANNUAL REVIEW     0;16 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Enter veteran's participation in the annual VIST review. 
              DESCRIPTION:
                                This field allows you to enter information regarding the veteran's participation in the annual VIST review in your program.  


2041.7,16     IDENTIFICATION CARD    0;17 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      MAR 12, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Enter whether veteran has applied for a national, state, or local ID card for the legally blind. 
              DESCRIPTION:      The AFB form of identification is no longer available.  Individuals should apply at their state motor vehicle offices for non-drivers identification cards that serve the same purpose and provide legal identification 
                                comparable to the sighted person's drivers license.  


2041.7,17     BLINDED VETERANS ASSOCIATION 0;18 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Enter information regarding veteran's membership status with BVA. 
              DESCRIPTION:      This is the Congressionally chartered service organization established for blind veterans.  Although originally established for SC veterans, over the years the BVA has amended its bylaws and now allows all NSC veterans
                                with vision problems to join as equal members with a few significant exceptions including the necessity to be a SC veteran for blindness in order to stand for the offices of President and Vice President of the
                                organization.  


2041.7,18     COMMISSARY AND EXCHANGE 0;19 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Enter eligibility for and use of Commissary/Exchange. 
              DESCRIPTION:
                                These are privileges granted to SC veterans rated 100%.  A blind veteran may also select a sighted companion who will be admitted with a letter of proof by the eligible veteran.  


2041.7,19     NATIONAL CONSUMER GROUPS 0;20 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Enter veteran's awareness of and/or membership in one of the national consumer groups for/of the blind. 
              DESCRIPTION:
                                These are the principal advocacy organizations of and for the blind.  The American Council of the Blind, the National Federation of the Blind and the Guide Dog Users, Inc. are among the major organizations.  


2041.7,20     FREE POSTAGE           0;21 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Enter veteran's awareness of and/or use of the free mailing privileges for the blind. 
              DESCRIPTION:
                                This is the provision by which a blind person may send large print, Braille and taped materials free of postage to a person requiring these media. 


2041.7,21     PHONE DIRECTORY ASSISTANCE 0;22 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Enter veteran's use of free directory assistance. 
              DESCRIPTION:      This is the service available in most areas of the country enabling a blind customer to be waived of information charges on their residential phone.  You must apply for this service with both your local and long distance
                                carrier.  


2041.7,22     DOG GUIDE TRAINING     0;23 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Indicate veteran's knowledge of this O&M option if appropriate. 
              DESCRIPTION:
                                There are approximately 16 schools across the country that provide selection of, matching with and training in the use of guide dogs for legally blind persons. 


2041.7,23     HADLEY SCHOOL FOR THE BLIND 0;24 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Indicate veteran's awareness of this program. 
              DESCRIPTION:
                                This is an international correspondence school providing courses in many subject areas. Instructional materials are provided in Braille, large print and tape formats.  


2041.7,24     HANDICAP PARKING PLACARD 1;1 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Indicate if veteran has applied for this benefit. 
              DESCRIPTION:      This is a privilege granted to eligible disabled persons that will allow them to park in designated handicapped parking spaces or to park free of meter charges or to remain in time-restricted parking spaces beyond the 
                                posted limit with the display of the placard or with disabled license tags on the car.  The disabled person may but does not need to be the driver, so a blind person may obtain disabled tags or the placard for use in a 
                                vehicle he/she owns or in which he/she rides.  


2041.7,25     INCOME TAX DEDUCTION   1;2 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Indicate veteran's awareness of this benefit. 
              DESCRIPTION:      This is a provision in the IRS code that enables a legally blind person to take an extra amount in deductions from their long form tax return.  In the past this was a full dependent's deduction but was reduced in the IRS 
                                reforms of 1993 and is currently approximately $600.  


2041.7,26     NAT'L PARKS ADMISSION PERMIT 1;3 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Indicate veteran's awareness of this program. 
              DESCRIPTION:
                                This is a life-long permit a disabled person may obtain at any National park that will entitle them and any companions accompanying them in the same vehicle free admission to National parks.  


2041.7,27     RADIO READING SERVICE  1;4 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Indicate veteran's awareness of this program. 
              DESCRIPTION:      This is a service available in many parts of the country that provides materials such as the local paper and current publication read over a closed circuit radio receiver for which a special receiver must be obtained from
                                the service.  


2041.7,28     RECORDING FOR THE BLIND 1;5 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Indicate veteran's awareness of this program where appropriate. 
              DESCRIPTION:
                                This is a service that provides text and professional materials recorded on tape. 


2041.7,29     SOCIAL SECURITY        1;6 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      There are several SSA programs from which a blind veteran might benefit. 
              DESCRIPTION:      The Social Security Administration has several benefits a blind person may be eligible for including SSI and SSDI.  For blind persons receiving SSDI, the earning limit for gainful employment is higher than for other
                                disabled persons; currently it is $1000 a month.  


2041.7,30     TALKING BOOKS          1;7 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Indicate veteran's awareness of and participation in this program. 
              DESCRIPTION:
                                This is a service available from the National Library Service, Library of Congress that provides recorded books for persons unable to read regular print.  The NLS program also provides books and magazines in Braille.  


2041.7,31     VOTING RIGHTS          1;8 POINTER TO VIST CHECKLIST OPTIONS FILE (#2041.6) (Required)

              LAST EDITED:      FEB 11, 1998 
              HELP-PROMPT:      Indicate veteran's awareness of this issue. 
              DESCRIPTION:      A blind or visually impaired person has the right to be accompanied by the person of their choice into the voting booth to assist them in casting their vote.  There are some slight variations in some jurisdictions with 
                                respect to what forms of identification the escort must provide.  


2041.7,32     LOCAL BENEFITS AND SERVICES 2;0 POINTER Multiple #2041.732

              DESCRIPTION:      There are a variety of local programs, services and benefits from which a blind or visually impaired veteran may benefit.  These vary widely throughout the country and it is important to be familiar with those in your area
                                in order to provide blind veterans the greatest array of services.  


